{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 16:36:10.135360", "event": "llm_start", "prompts": ["System: You are an expert network engineer.\nYour task is to submit the final solution for this network problem based on the diagnosis reported provided.\nCarefully review the diagnosis results and ensure that your submission is accurate and complete.\nYou must strictly follow the submission format and call the submit() tool to submit your solution.\nHuman: Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnostic report\nObjective: assess network health, detect anomalies, localize faulty device(s), and identify likely root cause(s). Tools used: host network configs, ping/reachability sweeps, router BGP and routing tables, DNS query, HTTP test, and netstat on servers.\n\nExecutive summary\n- Control/forwarding plane: BGP sessions are up across the fabric and the expected service prefixes (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24) are present in routing tables and seen by peers — no global BGP session flap observed.\n- DNS resolution works: client resolves web0.pod0 → 10.0.1.2 (dns_pod0 authoritative).\n- ICMP reachability: client → webserver and client → dns both succeed with low latency.\n- HTTP (TCP/80) fails from client: curl returns HTTP code 000 (connection failure/no HTTP response) while the web server process is reported as LISTEN on port 80.\n- Key anomaly: webserver host shows zero RX/TX packet counters on its interface despite pings and DNS-based connectivity tests indicating reachability. Routing tables also contain overlapping prefixes (/24 and /25) for the same service subnet on multiple routers.\n\nRelevant evidence (selected outputs)\n- Reachability (summary from sweeps)\n  - client_0 → dns_pod0: 4/4 packets, 0% loss, rtt_avg 3.123 ms\n  - client_0 → webserver0_pod0: 4/4 packets, 0% loss, rtt_avg 1.526 ms\n  - dns_pod0 → webserver0_pod0: 4/4 packets, 0% loss, rtt_avg 2.075 ms\n\n- DNS resolution (from client)\n  - Server: 10.0.0.2\n  - Name: web0.pod0\n  - Address: 10.0.1.2\n\n- HTTP test (from client)\n  - curl -w '%{http_code} %{time_total}': \"000 0.073162\"\n    - http_code 000 indicates the connection failed or was closed before an HTTP response.\n\n- Webserver (webserver0_pod0) local state\n  - ifconfig / ip addr: eth0 inet 10.0.1.2/24\n    - eth0 counters: RX packets 0 bytes 0, TX packets 0 bytes 0\n  - netstat -tuln: shows a process listening on 0.0.0.0:80 (python http.server present and LISTENing)\n\n- DNS server (dns_pod0) local state\n  - ifconfig: eth0 inet 10.0.0.2/24 (normal)\n  - netstat: named is listening on 10.0.0.2:53 and on 127.0.0.1 as expected\n\n- BGP / routing plane (representative lines)\n  - BGP sessions are established. Example from super_spine_router_0:\n    - Neighbors 172.16.0.1 (AS65100) and 172.16.0.3 (AS65101) — both Up, prefixes received (PfxRcd) reported.\n  - Routing tables contain both 10.0.1.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/25 entries in multiple routers:\n    - Several routers show: B>* 10.0.1.0/24 [...] and also B>* 10.0.1.0/25 [...]\n    - At least one leaf shows 10.0.1.0/24 as directly connected and also a 10.0.1.0/25 entry (oddly attached to lo on that router).\n\nObserved anomalies and inconsistencies\n1) Application-level TCP (HTTP) failure while lower-layer connectivity works\n   - ICMP and DNS path checks succeed to 10.0.1.2, but an HTTP client gets no response (curl code 000).\n   - The HTTP server process is listening on 0.0.0.0:80 on the webserver host while the client still cannot establish an HTTP session.\n\n2) Host interface counters inconsistent with reachability\n   - webserver0_pod0's interface shows RX/TX packet counters at zero (eth0: RX 0 TX 0) despite pings in the reachability report indicating successful ICMP to that host. This is an internal inconsistency that suggests either:\n     - the reported interface statistics are stale/out-of-sync with the test moment, or\n     - the ping/ICMP we observed terminated at some intermediate device (or was answered by a different entity), or\n     - the webserver's network namespace or interface where the application is listening is not the same interface being tested (namespace/namespace binding mismatch).\n\n3) Overlapping/duplicate prefixes in routing tables\n   - Several routers show both 10.0.1.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/25 in their routing tables (both BGP-learned or locally connected). Overlapping prefixes of different lengths for the same service subnet can result in inconsistent next-hop selection and asymmetric forwarding depending on where the more-specific (/25) route is installed. Also a /25 marked as connected to lo on a router is suspicious and likely a misconfiguration/artefact.\n\nLocalization of fault (most likely affected components)\n- Primary suspect: webserver host (webserver0_pod0) and/or the leaf/router adjacent to that host (leaf_router_0_1).\n  - Rationale: DNS resolves to 10.0.1.2 (webserver host); ping to that IP succeeds; webserver process shows LISTEN on port 80; nevertheless TCP/80 fails. The host's eth0 counters at zero suggest the host is not receiving TCP SYNs (or the statistics are not updated for that traffic path), or the process is bound to a different namespace/interface than the one actually reachable for ICMP — both point to a host/local configuration problem or port-specific filtering at the leaf/router.\n\n- Secondary suspect: intermediate router ACLs or filter that selectively blocks TCP/80\n  - Rationale: If host interface counters truly remain zero while pings succeed, one possible explanation is an ACL or an iptables rule on a router that filters 3-tuple TCP traffic but not ICMP. However, the presence of overlapping/more-specific routes (/25 vs /24) could also direct TCP to a different next-hop or blackhole in certain cases.\n\n- Control plane (BGP) and DNS service (dns_pod0) are healthy\n  - BGP neighbors are up and prefixes are exchanged.\n  - DNS resolved correctly from client and the DNS server is listening normally.\n\nMost likely root cause(s) (ranked)\n1) Host/network namespace or binding mismatch on webserver0_pod0\n   - Evidence: webserver process LISTENs on 0.0.0.0:80, but eth0 shows zero counters; ICMP reachability exists but TCP not observed by host. This is consistent with the server listening in a different network namespace or on an interface not attached to the routed path.\n\n2) Layer-3/ACL or port-filtering on the path (leaf_router_0_1 or upstream) specifically blocking TCP/80\n   - Evidence: HTTP fails while ICMP works; selective blocking at an intermediate device would explain successful ping but failed TCP connect. The presence of duplicate/overlapping prefixes could create a path that hits a node with a restrictive policy.\n\n3) Routing ambiguity caused by overlapping prefixes (10.0.1.0/24 vs 10.0.1.0/25) producing inconsistent next-hops or asymmetric forwarding\n   - Evidence: Multiple routers show both /24 and /25 for the same service subnet. If some devices use the /25 and others the /24, certain traffic types could be forwarded differently (e.g., replies taking different path), leading to connection failures despite ICMP showing partial success.\n\nAdditional notes / anomalies to be aware of\n- Repeated and numerous LISTEN entries for named on dns_pod0 (netstat) — likely normal if bind has multiple worker sockets, but high multiplicity is notable if unexpected.\n- Some routing table entries show prefixes learned and also advertised (PfxRcd and PfxSnt counts) — BGP looks generally stable with no obvious session problems.\n\nConclusion\n- The fabric control plane (BGP) and basic IP connectivity (ICMP, DNS) are working; the service (HTTP) is not reachable from the client.\n- The fault localizes to the webserver host and/or the immediate forwarding plane (leaf_router_0_1). The strongest evidence points to a host-level network namespace/binding mismatch or selective TCP/80 filtering on the path. Overlapping 10.0.1.0/24 and /25 prefixes in the routing plane are a secondary concern that could contribute to inconsistent forwarding.\n- Recommended next steps (data collection only, not remediations): confirm webserver process network namespace and binding, check host iptables/firewall and kernel packet counters while reproducing a failed TCP connection (tcpdump on host and adjacent leaf), and inspect ACLs/config on leaf_router_0_1 for TCP port filtering and verify which route (/24 vs /25) is installed in FIB on each hop. (I can collect those artifacts if you want me to proceed.)\n\nIf you want, I can now run targeted checks (tcpdump/tail logs, inspect iptables, show specific router ACLs or exact BGP route entries and FIB lookups) to further narrow between the host-namespace vs path-filter hypotheses., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available."], "metadata": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
